The paper focuses on the development of IT solutions for older adults, which falls under the category of human-computer interaction (cs.HC). The proposed method, SPIRAL, involves a participatory approach and user empowerment, which aligns with the category of cybernetics (cs.CY) and software engineering (cs.SE). The paper also mentions the use of a bootstrapped Living Lab concept, which falls under the category of social and information networks (cs.SI). Finally, the paper discusses the limitations of new and emerging startup environments, which could be categorized under the category of computational complexity (cs.CC).
